<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>com.apple.security.device.audio-input</key>
  <true/>
  <!-- The four entitlements below are the standard set for shipping a
       PyInstaller-bundled binary under hardened runtime with ad-hoc
       signing on macOS Sequoia. Each addresses a specific point where
       AMFI / dyld will SIGKILL the process otherwise:

       disable-library-validation: PyInstaller extracts Python.framework
         into /tmp/_MEI*/ at runtime; hardened runtime rejects the dlopen
         with "different Team IDs" since the framework wasn't co-signed
         with our ad-hoc identifier.

       allow-unsigned-executable-memory: PyInstaller's own bootloader
         maps and executes its decompressed bytecode/extension blob from
         memory pages that aren't backed by a signed file.

       allow-jit: numba (transitive dep via mlx-whisper) JIT-compiles
         host code at runtime; without this entitlement the JIT alloc
         is killed.

       allow-dyld-environment-variables: PyInstaller injects DYLD_*
         vars to point dyld at its bundled libs; hardened runtime
         strips these unless the entitlement is granted.

       Dev machine doesn't see any of these because TCC/Gatekeeper trust
       caching exempts locally-built binaries — so neither the smoke test
       nor `tccutil reset` clean-machine test surfaces them. They only
       fire on a truly remote install. -->
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
